WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.760
Welcome everyone, my name is Albert Rapp. I am a consultant based in Germany and

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:10.560
you may know me from the content that I share online on YouTube or LinkedIn.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:15.560
Today I want to talk to you about breaking data identities, which means

00:00:15.560 --> 00:00:19.600
that I want to help you appreciate programming languages other than your

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:24.040
preferred one. And to do so I want to share a story that I've learned during

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:29.879
my PhD. You see, until last year I was a PhD student in mathematics, specialized

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:35.439
in the field of probability and stats, which is one field among many others

00:00:35.439 --> 00:00:41.200
like algebra, calculus and so on. And I had such a strong identity of being

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:47.119
someone from this one particular field that I refused to read papers from other

00:00:47.119 --> 00:00:51.520
fields because I felt like these are not for me, I don't know anything about that,

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:56.840
so I can't read them and they don't really have anything to offer for me. But

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:01.639
as I refused to read all of these papers, at some point I acknowledged that I

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:06.320
should probably read them to find ideas that might help me solve my problem. And

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:11.919
it turned out that often these other areas had something to share and helped

00:01:11.919 --> 00:01:18.680
me solve my own problem from my field. And this is where I learned that it is

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:24.160
not necessarily when it comes to solving a problem, it isn't about working with a

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:29.040
particular tool or being in a particular area, it is about bringing

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:34.120
things together to get things done. And even though I already made this

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:38.239
experience and you'd think I'd know better, when it came to programming I

00:01:38.239 --> 00:01:43.519
fell into the same mindset trap where I had this one programming language, in my

00:01:43.519 --> 00:01:48.879
case R, where I felt like I can use this for everything and I don't need to know

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:53.760
about anything else. But just like it was a mistake to think that I am only

00:01:53.919 --> 00:01:58.599
someone from probability and stats and I cannot and won't do anything else, it is

00:01:58.599 --> 00:02:04.080
a mistake to not appreciate that our programming languages can help you and

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:09.399
have something to share inside of your project, even if you still have one

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:13.880
preferred language. And for example, if you work on a particular problem, then

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:18.759
for example if you work with reports, then you might want to use HTML and CSS

00:02:18.759 --> 00:02:23.639
to make things look pretty. Or if you want to do machine learning and AI, then

00:02:23.639 --> 00:02:28.000
Python might have something for you. And if you build web apps, for example in

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.960
R or Shiny, then it can still help you to bring in tiny nuggets of JavaScript into

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:40.919
your project to get things done faster or make it easier. And the thing is you

00:02:40.919 --> 00:02:44.679
usually like a particular language because the frameworks that are

00:02:44.679 --> 00:02:49.039
implemented in that language are so nice. For example, if you are into data

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:52.960
visualization, then you might like the grammar of graphics, which in R is

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:57.479
implemented in ggplot. And it turns out in Python there's a library called

00:02:57.479 --> 00:03:01.919
plot9, which does the exact same thing. That means it implements the grammar of

00:03:01.919 --> 00:03:07.399
graphics. And in these two packages it's even particularly nice because they use

00:03:07.399 --> 00:03:12.399
the exact same code to implement this framework. And when it comes to data

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:17.559
wrangling, you might like to use dplyr in R because it uses verbs like mutate

00:03:17.559 --> 00:03:22.440
and chains things together with pipe. And there you might have to, if you go into

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:26.960
other languages like Python, you might have to do some switching of the

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:32.279
terminologies by using dots instead of our pipe operator and using the with

00:03:32.279 --> 00:03:38.080
columns function instead of the mutate function. But in general, the ideas of

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:41.679
chaining things together can still be achieved in a different language. And I

00:03:41.679 --> 00:03:45.559
wish I had more time to focus on different frameworks and how they

00:03:45.559 --> 00:03:50.000
transcend programming languages. But as I don't have the time, I will put up a

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.800
link that you can follow to get a little guide of how to go from R to some

00:03:55.800 --> 00:04:02.119
other language like JavaScript or Python or HTML and CSS. But for now I

00:04:02.119 --> 00:04:05.839
hope I have convinced you that it's totally okay to have one preferred

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:10.559
language. This will never go away. But it's also great to appreciate what other

00:04:10.559 --> 00:04:15.279
languages can give you and that it might not be as hard as you'd think to bring

00:04:15.279 --> 00:04:19.320
nuggets from those languages into your projects. Thank you for your attention

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:22.519
and have a great conference!

